3140:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****         /* This function should not be called by application code hence the
3141:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          * 'Restricted' in its name.  It is not part of the public API.  It is
3142:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          * designed for use by kernel code, and has special calling requirements.
3143:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          * It can result in vListInsert() being called on a list that can only
3144:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          * possibly ever have one item in it, so the list will be fast, but even
3145:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          * so it should be called with the scheduler locked and not from a critical
3146:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          * section. */
3147:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c **** 
3148:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****         /* Only do anything if there are no messages in the queue.  This function
3149:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          *  will not actually cause the task to block, just place it on a blocked
3150:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          *  list.  It will not block until the scheduler is unlocked - at which
3151:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          *  time a yield will be performed.  If an item is added to the queue while
3152:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          *  the queue is locked, and the calling task blocks on the queue, then the
3153:../Core/FreeRTOS-Kernel/queue.c ****          *  calling task will be immediately unblocked when the queue is unlocked. */
